<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-08-19T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-08-19T13:00:00-05:00" n="514" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d514">
                                <note rend="inline" type="source">765.84/875: Telegram</note>
                                <head>
                                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Marriner</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                            State</gloss>
                                    </hi>
                                </head>
                                <opener>
                                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                                        <placeName>
                                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-08-19T19:00:00+01:00">August 19, 1935—7 p.m.</date>
                                        <lb/> [Received August 19—4 p.m.]</dateline>
                                </opener>
                                <p>711. French press reactions to the break-up of the tripartite
                                    negotiations show little sign of being influenced by internal
                                    political considerations. From left to right the newspapers
                                    express sorrow at the inability of the three powers to arrive at
                                    conclusion and show a tendency to place the principal cause for
                                    failure upon the divergence between Anglo-Italian viewpoints.
                                    This allows them to show France as the disappointed peacemaker.
                                    If anything the general tendency is to infer that Italy should
                                    be leniently and considerately treated without compromising
                                    France’s devotion and duty to the League.</p>
                                <closer>
                                    <signed>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Marriner</hi>
                                    </signed>
                                </closer>
                            </div>
                            </body></text></TEI>